  "signature": "ed25519:4b8e3f2a1c9d7e6f5a4b3c2d1e0f9a8b7c6d5e4f3a2b1c0d9e8f7a6b5c4d3e2f",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Version-controlled FEA code with documented release notes, regression test suite covering all contact and material nonlinearities used in the pedicle screw model, and ISO 9001-compliant change-control records. Gradation 2 requires evidence of systematic QA process; Gradation 3 additionally requires independent verification of regression tests.",
      "rationale": "The modeling ensemble (Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2, internal FDA FEA solver) operates under ISO 9001-certified quality management systems. Regression test suites covering nonlinear contact and Ti-6Al-4V material behavior are executed at each release. Version control via Git with signed commits. Achieved Gradation 3 exceeds the required Gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark solutions for beam bending and Hertzian contact reproduced to within 1% of analytical solutions. Gradation 2 requires at least two independent benchmark problems relevant to the physics of the COU.",
      "rationale": "Two benchmark problems were executed: (1) cantilever beam under end load compared to Euler-Bernoulli solution (error < 0.3%); (2) cylindrical contact stress compared to Hertz analytical solution (error < 0.8%). Both benchmarks are directly relevant to the bending-dominated loading of the F1717 construct. Achieved level matches required level."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrating that QoI change between successive refinement levels is less than 2% for all three quantities of interest (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm). Gradation 2 requires a convergence study on the final mesh; Gradation 3 additionally requires Richardson extrapolation or equivalent formal error estimation.",
      "rationale": "A four-level mesh refinement study was conducted on the pedicle screw shank and rod interface regions. Richardson extrapolation applied to all three QoIs yielded discretization errors below 0.9%. The final production mesh (1.2M elements, quadratic tetrahedral) was selected at the knee of the convergence curve. GCI values < 1.5% for all QoIs. Achieved Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Residual tolerances documented and shown to be at least three orders of magnitude below QoI sensitivity thresholds. Iterative solver convergence verified for each load step in the nonlinear analysis.",
      "rationale": "Newton-Raphson iterations converged to force residual < 1e-6 N and displacement residual < 1e-8 mm for all load steps. Solver settings documented in the simulation plan. No divergence events observed across all 11 experimental replicate simulations."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation plan reviewed by an analyst independent of the model developer, with documented sign-off. All boundary condition and material assignments verified against the simulation plan prior to execution.",
      "rationale": "A peer-review checklist was completed by a second analyst (not the model developer) covering geometry import, material assignments (Ti-6Al-4V elastic-plastic, UHMWPE block), boundary conditions replicating the F1717 fixture, and load application. No discrepancies found. Simulation plan revision history archived."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model form selection justified by literature precedent for pedicle screw FEA under bending-dominated loading, with explicit documentation of assumptions (e.g., bonded vs. frictional contacts, material constitutive law). Gradation 3 requires sensitivity analysis quantifying the impact of at least one key model form assumption on each QoI.",
      "rationale": "Frictional contact (μ=0.2, Coulomb) was selected for screw-rod interface based on published tribological data for Ti-Ti interfaces. Bonded contact was used at the set-screw locking interface, consistent with the fully-tightened experimental condition. Sensitivity analysis showed that varying μ from 0.15 to 0.25 changed predicted stiffness by < 1.8% and yield force by < 2.3%, confirming robustness of the model form choice."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from peer-reviewed literature or direct coupon testing, with uncertainty bounds propagated through the model. Geometric inputs derived from calibrated CMM measurements of the actual test hardware. Gradation 3 requires formal uncertainty quantification of input parameters and their effect on QoIs.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V elastic modulus (114 GPa ± 3 GPa) and yield strength (880 MPa ± 15 MPa) sourced from ASTM F136 material certification data for the specific lot used in testing. CMM measurements of screw geometry (n=3 screws) showed dimensional variation < 0.02 mm. Monte Carlo propagation (n=500 samples) confirmed that input uncertainty contributes < 3% to QoI variance, dominated by yield strength variability."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test sample population (N≥10) drawn from production-representative hardware with documented traceability to manufacturing lot. Gradation 2 requires N≥5 with lot traceability; Gradation 3 additionally requires dimensional characterization of each test article.",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs tested across two independent laboratories. All screws drawn from the same production lot (lot traceability documented). Each screw measured by CMM prior to testing; dimensional data used to individualize FEA geometry where variation exceeded 0.05 mm. Achieved Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conducted under at least two distinct loading configurations or environmental conditions representative of the COU envelope. Gradation 2 requires documentation that test conditions bound the intended use conditions.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single ASTM F1717 standard configuration (35 mm offset, room temperature, displacement-controlled at 5 mm/min). Only one test condition was evaluated, which does not fully bound the clinical use envelope (e.g., dynamic loading, varied offsets). This factor was assessed at Gradation 1 and represents the primary credibility gap identified in this assessment. The gap is acknowledged in the decision record and accepted given that the static F1717 test is the regulatory standard for this device class."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "Simulation inputs (geometry, material properties, boundary conditions, loading rate) were mapped directly to experimentally measured and controlled quantities. The 35 mm offset was confirmed by fixture measurement. Displacement rate of 5 mm/min was verified against test machine calibration records. Material properties input to the model are traceable to the same lot as the test hardware. No unresolved discrepancies between simulation inputs and experimental conditions were identified. The equivalency assessment confirms that differences between model inputs and test conditions are within measurement uncertainty bounds, supporting the validity of direct QoI comparison."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison of all three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) using both percent difference (<10%) and validation metric E/uval < 1.96. Gradation 3 requires that the comparison accounts for both experimental variability and model prediction uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "All three QoIs met both acceptance criteria: stiffness difference 4.2% (E/uval=1.31), yield force difference 6.8% (E/uval=1.74), force at 40 mm difference 3.9% (E/uval=1.18). Experimental variability (CV < 8% for all QoIs) and model prediction uncertainty (from input UQ) were combined in quadrature for the uval denominator. All comparisons fall within the pre-specified acceptance bounds."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs selected are directly linked to the clinical and regulatory decision criteria for pedicle screw construct performance. Gradation 2 requires documented justification; Gradation 3 additionally requires traceability to regulatory guidance or predicate device submissions.",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are the primary outputs specified in ASTM F1717 and referenced in FDA guidance for spinal implant submissions. Traceability to FDA's 2019 guidance document on spinal implant testing is documented in the simulation plan. These QoIs directly inform the regulatory decision on substantial equivalence."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities replicate the geometry, loading, and boundary conditions of the COU with documented justification for any deviations. Gradation 3 requires that the validation domain is shown to encompass the COU domain for all critical parameters.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity uses the identical screw geometry, rod diameter, and UHMWPE block as the COU device. Loading and boundary conditions replicate the regulatory standard test (ASTM F1717). The validation domain (non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw, 35 mm offset) directly corresponds to the COU. No extrapolation beyond the validated domain is required for the regulatory decision. Achieved Gradation 3."
    }
  ],
